rity lifestyle, his enemies sought every chance to undermine him. Eventually, facing a capital charge of impiety, Alcibiades escaped to the enemy, Sparta. There he traded military intelligence for safety until, suspected of seducing a Spartan queen, he was forced to flee again—this time to Greece’s long-term foes, the Persians. Miraculously, though, he engineered a recall to Athens as Supreme Commander, but—suffering a reversal—he took flight to Thrace, where he lived as a warlord. At last in Anatolia, tracked by his enemies, he died naked and alone in a hail of arrows. As he follows Alcibiades’ journeys crisscrossing the Mediterranean from mainland Greece to Syracuse, Sardis, and Byzantium, Stuttard weaves together the threads of Alcibiades’ adventures against a backdrop of cultural splendor and international chaos. Navigating often contradictory evidence, Nemesis provides a coherent and spellbinding account of a life that has gripped historians, storytellers, and artists for more than two thousand years.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Historical.2bisacsh  aAncient Greece.  aAristophanes.  aAthenians.  aChithrafarna.  aFarnavaz II.  aIonia.  aNicias.  aPeloponnesian War.  aPericles.  aPersia.  aPersians.  aPlato.  aSamos.  aSicily.  aSparta.  aSpartans.  aSyracuse.  aThrace.  aThracians.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060662140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067491968640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674919686423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674919686.jpg  a978-3-11-060662-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles